[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by mobuchowski

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/45|#45 [PROPOSAL] Standarize custom facet naming>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong><br /> Main motivation of this proposal is making sure that custom facets in different implementations of OpenLineage clients for the same data source have the same name. Another advantage will be decreased chance of different facets name colliding.</p> <p><strong>Proposed implementation</strong><br /> I propose that custom facets should follow name pattern <code>{prefix}{name}{entity}Facet</code> PascalCased, where</p> <p>• Prefix must be distinct identifier named after the project • Name is the desired facet name • Entity is the core OpenLineage entity for which the facet will be attached</p> <p>Important aspect for OpenLineage consumers is standarizing JSON key naming.<br /> I propose to follow pattern <code>{prefix}_{name}</code> snakeCased.</p> <p>Example of custom facet following both patterns: <code>BigQueryStatisticsJobFacet</code> and <code>bigQuery_statistics</code></p>
Labels
proposal

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by wslulciuc

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/61|#61 Releasing via CI>
<p>With the upcoming release of OpenLineage <code>0.1.0</code>, we'll want to publish our artifacts via CI. Below, I propose the following release steps:</p> <ol><li>Bump the version in <code>gradle.properties</code> for <code>openlineage-java</code> and in <code>setup.py</code> for <code>openlineage-python</code></li><li>Tag the release with <code>X.Y.Z</code> on <code>main</code> branch</li><li>Prepare the next development version</li><li>CI kickoffs release jobs to publish artifacts</li> </ol> <p>&gt; <strong>Note:</strong> The steps outlined above are inspired by the release steps for <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/blob/main/RELEASING.md"><code>Marquez</code></a>. Also, for <strong>step 1</strong>, we can reference <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/blob/main/new-version.sh"><code>new-version.sh</code></a> used on Marquez releases.</p> <p><a href="https://github.com/mobuchowski">@mobuchowski</a>: You've already made some great additions to our CI config, this is just to capture the CI release flow.</p>

<p><strong>Purpose:</strong><br /> We need to define how the OpenLineage spec gets versioned and published.<br /> Some requirements:</p> <p>• The OpenLineage spec and related libraries are in the OpenLineage repo. • The OpenLineage spec version should change only when the spec itself changes. • The libraries in the repo change more frequently than the spec (including when the spec changes). • We want to version the OpenLineage spec independently of the api spec. • The mechanism to version and publish the OpenLineage core spec, should apply to publishing custom facets.</p> <p><strong>Proposed implementation</strong><br /> I have started a google doc to make it easier to collaborate:<br /> <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1inhmb90SB62VyYf8nkkpjBDPpyr2wxkIXQ_AFIQiF9I/edit">https://docs.google.com/document/d/1inhmb90SB62VyYf8nkkpjBDPpyr2wxkIXQ_AFIQiF9I/edit</a><br /> please comment in the doc.</p>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by wslulciuc

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/73|#73 Move Marquez integrations to OpenLineage>
<p>The <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez">Marquez</a> community is excited to announce that the following integrations will be moved to the wider OpenLineage ecosystem:</p> <p>• <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/tree/main/integrations/airflow"><code>marquez-airflow</code></a>: A library that integrates Airflow DAGs to emit OpenLineage metadata. • <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/tree/main/integrations/spark"><code>marquez-spark</code></a>: A spark agent using jvm instrumentation to emit OpenLineage metadata. • <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/tree/main/integrations/common"><code>marquez-integration-common</code></a>: Shared code across integrations. • <code>marquez-dbt-snowflake</code>: A library that integrates with DBT to emit OpenLineage metadata for Snowflake. • <code>marquez-dbt-bigquery</code>: A library that integrates with DBT to emit OpenLineage metadata for BigQuery.</p> <p>&gt; Note: You can view the integrations in the Marquez repo under <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/tree/main/integrations"><code>marquez/integrations/</code></a>. Marquez is an official reference implementation of the OpenLineage API and all the integrations adopt the OpenLineage standard.</p> <p><strong>Why are the integrations being moved to OpenLineage?</strong></p> <p>The OpenLineage standard was influenced by Marquez's underlying data model (<em>datasets</em>, <em>jobs</em>, <em>runs</em>) while also drawing inspiration from the projects lineage ingestion API. With OpenLineage now a standalone project under <a href="https://lfaidata.foundation">LFAI &amp; Data Foundation</a>, we've decided that now would be the right time to move the integrations over as more and more integrations are being added to the <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/projects/1">projects roadmap</a> (<em>Looker</em>, <em>Flink</em>, <em>Beam</em>, etc). This would also allow for the OpenLineage community to grow and learn from existing integration implementations, prioritize bug fixes, propose new integrations and changes to the spec, etc.</p> <p><strong>What is the timeline for moving the integrations to OpenLineage?</strong></p> <p>Below we outline a high-level timeline of moving the integrations to OpenLineage. We encourage everyone to provide feedback and express any concerns you may have by commenting in this issue:</p> <p>☐ Release Marquez <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/projects/12"><code>0.16.0</code></a> ☐ Move the following integrations from Marquez to OpenLineage: ☐ <code>marquez-airflow</code> ☐ <code>marquez-spark</code> ☐ <code>marquez-integration-common</code> ☐ <code>marquez-dbt-snowflake</code> ☐ <code>marquez-dbt-bigquery</code> ☐ Deprecate all integrations in Marquez, then link to the new location in the OpenLineage repo</p> <p>Then, going forward, new integrations and improvements will be made by open pull requests against the OpenLineage repo. <strong>Note that during this migration phase, existing Marquez specific functionality and environment variables will be maintained to ensure backwards compatibility. The main difference is that integration packages will get a new name: <code>openlineage-**</code> instead of <code>marquez-**</code></strong>.</p>
<a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage">OpenLineage/OpenLineage</a>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by julienledem

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/105|#105 [PROPOSAL] package level job metadata>
<p><strong>Purpose</strong></p> <p>To expose information like the version of the job and its source repository, we need a mechanism to provide metadata in the job package when deploying to a scheduler.<br /> An example of this is deploying DAGs to an Airflow instance, but this is applicable to all package deployments in general.<br /> In some instances workflows/jobs are directly pulled from a source control system from the scheduler allowing some metadata to be inferred from the environment. In other instances, the jobs are packaged and deployed to a scheduler (example: google cloud composer or astronomer). This doc concerns the later case of providing metadata related to the source code of the job at build time.</p> <p>(This is based on a Marquez proposal: <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/issues/825">MarquezProject/marquez#825</a>)</p> <p><strong>Proposal</strong></p> <p>We define a metadata file to be added at the root of the package/deployment location. This file is named <strong>.OpenLineage.job.facets.json</strong> and is a json file with the following initial properties (that can be expanded later).</p> <p>This also adds "repoUrl", "path", "version", "branch" to the existing SourceCodeLocation facet.</p> <p><a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/6909a3da92ec69e464a90982f6b2c3727353955e/spec/OpenLineage.json#L339-L362">OpenLineage/spec/OpenLineage.json</a></p> <p>Lines 339 to 362 in &lt;/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/commit/6909a3da92ec69e464a90982f6b2c3727353955e|6909a3d&gt;</p> <p><strong>Properties:</strong></p> <p>• <strong>sourceCodeLocation.type</strong>: the source control system<br /> Examples: GIT, SVN, ... • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.url</strong>: the full http URL to locate the file<br /> Example: <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart/blob/693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691/dags/dummy_example.py">https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart/blob/693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691/dags/dummy<em>example.py</a> • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.repoUrl</strong>: the URL to the repository<br /> Examples: • GIT: <a href="mailto:git@github.com">git@github.com</a>:{org}/{repo}.git or <a href="https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D.git|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}.git">https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D.git|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}.git</a> • SVN: svn://&lt;your</em>ip&gt;/&lt;repository_name&gt; • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.path</strong>: the path in the repo containing the source files<br /> Example: path/to/my/dags<br /> It is intended that we can reconstruct a URL from that path pointing to the file defining a job. <a href="https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D/tree/%7Bversion%7D/%7Bpath%7D/%7Bfile|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}/tree/{version}/{path}/{file">https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D/tree/%7Bversion%7D/%7Bpath%7D/%7Bfile|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}/tree/{version}/{path}/{file</a> path in the package} • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.version</strong>: the current version deployed (not a branch name, the actual unique version)<br /> Examples: • Git: the git sha • Svn: the revision number • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.tag</strong>: optional tag name<br /> Examples: {tag name} • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.branch</strong>:optional branch name</p> <p><strong>JSON Schema</strong></p> <pre><code>{ "$schema": "&lt;https://json-schema.org/draft/2019-09/schema&gt;", "type": "object", "properties": { "sourceCodeLocation": { "type": "object", "properties": { "type": { "type": "string" }, "url": { "type": "string" }, "repoUrl": { "type": "string" }, "path": { "type": "string" }, "version": { "type": "string" }, "tag": { "type": "string" }, "branch": { "type": "string" } }, "required": [ "type", "url" ] } } } </code></pre> <p><strong>Example:</strong></p> <p>For the DAG defined at: <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart/blob/693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691/dags/dummy_example.py">https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart/blob/693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691/dags/dummy_example.py</a></p> <pre><code>{ "sourceCodeLocation": { "type": "GIT", "url": "&lt;https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart/blob/693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691/dags/dummy_example.py&gt;", "repoUrl": "&lt;https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart.git&gt;", "path": "dags", "version": "693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691", "branch": "master" } } </code></pre>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by wslulciuc

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/108|#108 Add support for `pandas.read_sql`>
<p>Let's add support for the Panda wrapper method <a href="https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.read_sql.html"><code>read_sql</code></a>:</p> <pre><code>pandas.read_sql(sql, con, index_col=None, coerce_float=True, params=None, parse_dates=None, columns=None, chunksize=None) </code></pre> <p>Since we have access to the <code>sql</code> at time of method execution, we can easily parse the SQL to capture the in / out tables before sending an OpenLineage event. We also have access to <code>columns</code> (if present) on table reads and may also want to support <code>read_sql_table</code> and <code>read_sql_query</code> (for backward compatibility).</p>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by mobuchowski

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/120|#120 SchemaDatasetFacet: relax type requirement>
<p>Right now, type property for schema field is required:<br /> <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/main/spec/OpenLineage.json#L462">https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/main/spec/OpenLineage.json#L462</a></p> <p>It's easy to imagine cases where this restriction disallows us from emitting useful information. For example, <code>dbt</code> metadata sometimes does not always emit types. Another example might be etl job that selects subset of columns - it would be nice to see which ones are selected, even if we don't know their types.</p>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Pull request opened by julienledem

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/pull/140|#140 Add mechanism to enforce spec versioning>
<p>This modifies the code generator to:</p> <p>• always use the local version of the spec • issue a warning if the spec is not public at $id • verify that the spec matches the one published at $id if available • fail the build if the spec does not match to require changing the version.</p> <p>This will guarantee that we don't reuse published specs.<br /> It also removes the need for the code to be pushed to the repo for the build to work.</p> <p>Signed-off-by: Julien Le Dem <a href="mailto:julien@apache.org">julien@apache.org</a></p>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by julienledem

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/153|#153 [PROPOSAL] Version facets independently of the core spec>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong><br /> The OpenLineage core spec is versioned using a version URL in the <code>$id</code> field:<br /> See:</p> <p>• <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/main/spec/Versioning.md">https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/main/spec/Versioning.md</a> • <a href="https://openlineage.io/spec/1-0-0/OpenLineage.json">https://openlineage.io/spec/1-0-0/OpenLineage.json</a></p> <pre><code>{ "$schema": "&lt;https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema&gt;", "$id": "&lt;https://openlineage.io/spec/1-0-0/OpenLineage.json&gt;", </code></pre> <p>Currently all the core facets are also defined in that same core spec.</p> <p>This means that the core spec gets a new version whenever a facet is changed along with every other facet.<br /> We'd rather have the core spec and each facet versioned independently so that their version changes only when they change.<br /> This matches much better the use cases for using the version number.</p> <p>For example:</p> <p>• a consumer of OpenLineage would care only about the compatibility of the core spec, accept any version of any facet and handles specific facets independently. • a producer of a facet cares what version of the core model and that specific facet (core or custom) it is generating. • a consumer of a specific facet cares about the version of that specific facet and ignore changes to facets it does not consume.</p> <p><strong>Proposed implementation</strong></p> <p>This proposal is to move each core facet definition into its own file and use the same versioning mechanism (per file) as the core spec.</p> <p>This leaves the core spec to only contain the <code>LineageEvent</code> and related core entities (LineageEvent, Run, Job, Dataset) but none of the core facets.</p> <p>See for example:<br /> <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/789b55fc6e6e07d0aedbe130f775721829e83618/spec/OpenLineage.json">https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/789b55fc6e6e07d0aedbe130f775721829e83618/spec/OpenLineage.json</a><br /> This would be the spec that a consumer would implement to accept any facet version.<br /> This would ensure that the core spec version changes rarely, only when we add fields to the core model.<br /> Each facet would be versioned independently following the same versioning mechanism. Each facet version will change if and only if this particular facet schema changes. It also makes core facets and custom facets work exactly the same, they are just maintained in different repositories.</p> <p>Example:<br /> <a href="https://openlineage.io/spec/1-0-0/DatasetSchemaFacet.json">https://openlineage.io/spec/1-0-0/DatasetSchemaFacet.json</a></p> <pre><code>{ "$schema": "&lt;https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema&gt;", "$id": "&lt;https://openlineage.io/spec/1-0-0/DatasetSchemaFacet.json&gt;", "type": "object", "properties": { "schema": { "allOf": [ { "$ref": "&lt;https://openlineage.io/spec/1-0-0/OpenLineage.json#/definitions/DatasetFacet&gt;" }, { "type": "object", "properties": { "fields": { "description": "The fields of the table.", "type": "array", "items": { "type": "object", "properties": { "name": { "description": "The name of the field.", "type": "string", "example": "column1" }, "type": { "description": "The type of the field.", "type": "string", "example": "VARCHAR|INT|..." }, "description": { "description": "The description of the field.", "type": "string" } }, "required": [ "name", "type" ] } } } } ], "type": "object" }, } } } </code></pre>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by collado-mike

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/155|#155 [PROPOSAL] Add support for CloudSQL endpoint discovery/reporting>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong><br /> Accessing CloudSQL resources generally involves using a local proxy that does the authentication with the remote database endpoint. Database drivers will then create a URL like <code>&lt;postgres://localhost:5432/my_database&gt;</code>, which the OpenLineage integration will always report as <code>localhost</code> in the data source metadata.</p> <p>It won't be possible to detect the actual database location from the OpenLineage integration directly, but we can probably add some configuration option so that users can report the correct database location.</p> <p><strong>Proposed implementation</strong><br /> Add configuration option for user to report actual CloudSQL database location</p>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by collado-mike

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/168|#168 [PROPOSAL] Making the spark integration extensible>
<p>Ported from <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/issues/1192">MarquezProject/marquez#1192</a> . It's been updated to reflect the current status of the Spark integration.</p> <p><strong>Proposal</strong></p> <p>I propose a more extensible method of loading and discovering node visitors. The basic strategy is</p> <ol><li>Create a common interface for visiting logical plan nodes- something that extends the <code>PartitalFunction&amp;lt;LogicalPlan, List&amp;lt;Dataset&amp;gt;&amp;gt;</code> interface we already use</li><li>Take advantage of the JVM's <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/ServiceLoader.html">ServiceLoader</a> capabilities to enable implementations on the classpath to be found at runtime</li><li>Package node visitors in different subprojects that generate their own jars</li><li>Entrust Spark users to declare dependencies on the node visitors they need using the <code>spark.jars.packages</code> or <code>spark.jars</code> configuration properties</li> </ol> <p>The main advantages I see here are</p> <ol><li>Static typing, easy to read code, and easy unit testing</li><li>Extensible framework to support new integrations<br /> This point, I feel, is extremely important. While the single jar deployment is convenient, it creates an unnecessary barrier for users who want to take part in the OpenLineage ecosystem, but can't/won't contribute directly to ~Marquez or~ OpenLineage. This may be because</li> </ol> <p>• their company has strict open source contribution policies • they need to work with some proprietary, custom datasource. E.g., a robotics company might have a datasource specific to ROS topics that are particular to that company • they want to deploy their integration without going through the community review/release process<br /> Forcing developers to fork the repo in order to add custom integrations is a deterrent to building an ecosystem.</p> <ol start="3"><li>Adding integrations is less complex, as developers don't need to worry about, e.g., conflicting versions of Guava required by the <code>BigQueryRelation</code> and the <code>HBaseRelation</code>.</li> </ol> <p>The tradeoff here is that users need to declare the ~Marquez~OpenLineage integration dependencies and deploy them separately from the main jar. Statically typed dataset integrations should be loaded by the Spark <code>ClassLoader</code> (e.g., declared in the <code>spark.jars.packages</code> or <code>spark.jars</code> configuration) in order to link to the Datasource classes they depend on. In terms of developer experience, I don't think this pattern is foreign to Spark users today.</p> <p>Notably, nothing prohibits users from bundling their own superjars that contain all of their dependencies and deploying them to their Spark clusters. Similarly, nothing prevents integration authors from using reflection in their code. Users are given the freedom to extend and package their integrations in a way that suits them without enforcing an opaque, black-box model.</p> <p>~As a separate issue, we can consider changing the ~Marquez~OpenLineage agent to be loaded by the <code>spark.extraListeners</code> configuration. This would allow users to reference all of the ~Marquez~OpenLineage integration dependencies by specifying the listener and the node visitors in <code>spark.jars.packages</code> so that all of the classes are loaded by the Spark <code>ClassLoader</code>. That eliminates any confusion about which components need to be loaded by which <code>ClassLoader</code>. It also simplifies testing and could enable integration in serverless environments, such as AWS Glue, where users don't have access to modify the JVM arguments.~</p> <p>&gt; This has already been implemented</p> <p><strong>Packaging Spark Integrations</strong></p> <p>Spark integration packages need to create a file in <code>META-INF/services/marquez.spark.agent.lifecycle.plan.DatasetSource</code> which declares a list of classes that implement the <code>openlineage.spark.agent.lifecycle.plan.DatasetSource</code> interface. During startup, the main ~Marquez~OpenLineage agent uses the JVM <code>ServiceLoader</code> to find all service implementations on the classpath (we need to specifically check the Spark <code>URLClassloader</code> to find implementations loaded by Spark at runtime). Combining jars requires concatenating the contents of the <code>META-INF/services/marquez.spark.agent.lifecycle.plan.DatasetSource</code> files so that all implementations are listed.</p> <p><strong>Deploying Dependencies</strong></p> <p>~Currently, users deploy the Marquez integration by adding the <code>javaagent:&amp;lt;jar&amp;gt;=&lt;http://marquez_url/path/to/job&gt;</code> argument to their spark-submit args. That doesn't change with this proposal.~</p> <p>What does change is that users would be required to specify the integrations they require in their <code>spark.jars</code> or <code>spark.jars.packages</code> configuration. As an example, the airflow example in the README would look like this:</p> <pre><code>from uuid import uuid4 import os ... job_name = 'job_name' properties = { 'spark.extraListeners': 'openlineage.spark.agent.OpenLineageSparkListener', 'spark.jar.packages': 'io.openlineage:openlineage_spark:0.0.1', 'spark.openlineage.host': os.environ.get('MARQUEZ_URL'), 'spark.openlineage.namespace': os.getenv('MARQUEZ_NAMESPACE', 'default'), 'spark.openlineage.apiKey': os.environ.get('MARQUEZ_API_KEY'), 'spark.openlineage.parentRunId': "{{task_run_id(run_id, task)}}", 'spark.openlineage.parentJobName': '{{ task.task_id }}' } t1 = DataProcPySparkOperator( task_id=job_name, gcp_conn_id='google_cloud_default', project_id='project_id', cluster_name='cluster-name', region='us-west1', main='&lt;gs://bucket/your-prog.py&gt;', job_name=job_name, dataproc_pyspark_properties=properties, &lt;b&gt;#Both&lt;/b&gt; bigquery relation and bigquery openlineage integration declared here dataproc_pyspark_jars='&lt;gs://spark-lib/bigquery/spark-bigquery-latest_2.12.jar,gs://my_bucket/path/to/bigquery-integration.jar&gt;', dag=dag) </code></pre> <p>Alternatively, a cluster can be created by loading the correct jars into the Spark jars directory, as described in the <a href="https://github.com/GoogleCloudDataproc/initialization-actions/tree/master/connectors">BigQuery connector docs</a>. In the same way, the ~Marquez~OpenLineage integrations would need to be installed on the driver node. In either case, the person responsible for loading the bigquery jars on the classpath is also responsible for loading the Marquez integration. Dependencies can be bundled so that the Marquez integration and the BigQueryRelation class are all loaded in the same jar.</p>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by collado-mike

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/181|#181 [INTEGRATION] [Spark] Making the spark integration extensible>
<p><strong>Context</strong></p> <p>The Spark integration relies on instrumentation achieved by adding a jar to the <code>javaagent</code> argument on the command line when starting a Spark job. When the JVM starts up, the application <code>ClassLoader</code> loads both the instrumentation jar as well as the Spark, Hadoop, and other dependency jars that are on the classpath. When the <code>SparkContext</code> is loaded, Spark parses its own configuration and finds additional jars that have been specified, either on the command line or in a configuration map that can be populated at runtime. The jars are (sometimes) downloaded and added to a <code>MutableURLClassLoader</code> that is owned and managed by the <code>SparkContext</code>.</p> <p>Since the Marquez integration is loaded by the top level application <code>ClassLoader</code>, and Java’s <code>ClassLoaders</code> are ignorant of their child <code>ClassLoaders</code>, the integration is only able to find classes that are loaded by that top level <code>ClassLoader</code>. BigQuery and other dependencies may be specified in the <code>spark.jars</code> configuration, so that they are loaded by that child <code>MutableURLClassLoader</code>, hence invisible to the Marquez agent classes. While it is possible from the integration to detect that BigQuery classes are available, attempting to instantiate the classes that actually deal with those classes cause <code>NoClassDefFoundErrors</code>, since the <code>ClassLoader</code> can’t find the classes loaded by the child loader.</p> <p>The current workaround relies on <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez/pull/1180">instrumentation</a> to invoke methods from the parent <code>ClassLoader</code> without needing to directly access the <code>BigQueryRelation</code> class or related classes.</p> <p>I think the instrumentation approach has the following drawbacks</p> <ol><li>We lose type safety and the ability to easily unit test the instrumentation code</li><li>Failure to instrument the code at runtime leaves users blind to the missing dataset nodes</li><li>Isn't extensible to support other integrations</li> </ol> <p>To be fair, it has the following advantages</p> <ol><li>Only a single jar is needed at runtime</li><li>It's possible for a single jar to support multiple, statically non-compatible versions of the BigQuery integration using conditional checks (e.g., <code>if ( class.hasMethod("X")) generateXSpecificCode()</code>)</li> </ol> <p>Reflection has been suggested as an alternative strategy, but I think the pros/cons are largely the same as the instrumentation approach- it uses indirect method invocation to circumvent static type checking.</p> <p><strong>Proposal</strong></p> <p>Instead of instrumentation or reflection, I propose a more extensible method of loading and discovering node visitors. The basic strategy is</p> <ol><li>Create a common interface for visiting logical plan nodes- something that extends the <code>PartitalFunction&amp;lt;LogicalPlan, List&amp;lt;Dataset&amp;gt;&amp;gt;</code> interface we already use</li><li>Take advantage of the JVM's <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/ServiceLoader.html">ServiceLoader</a> capabilities to enable implementations on the classpath to be found at runtime</li><li>Package node visitors in different subprojects that generate their own jars</li><li>Entrust Spark users to declare dependencies on the node visitors they need using the <code>spark.jars.packages</code> or <code>spark.jars</code> configuration properties</li> </ol> <p>The main advantages I see here are</p> <ol><li>Static typing, easy to read code, and easy unit testing</li><li>Extensible framework to support new integrations<br /> This point, I feel, is extremely important. While the single jar deployment is convenient, it creates an unnecessary barrier for users who want to take part in the OpenLineage ecosystem, but can't/won't contribute directly to Marquez or OpenLineage. This may be because</li> </ol> <p>• their company has strict open source contribution policies • they need to work with some proprietary, custom datasource. E.g., a robotics company might have a datasource specific to ROS topics that are particular to that company • they want to deploy their integration without going through the community review/release process<br /> Forcing developers to fork the repo in order to add custom integrations is a deterrent to building an ecosystem.</p> <ol start="3"><li>Adding integrations is less complex, as developers don't need to worry about, e.g., conflicting versions of Guava required by the <code>BigQueryRelation</code> and the <code>HBaseRelation</code>.</li> </ol> <p>The tradeoff here is that users need to declare the Marquez integration dependencies and deploy them separately from the main agent jar. Statically typed dataset integrations should be loaded by the Spark <code>ClassLoader</code> (e.g., declared in the <code>spark.jars.packages</code> or <code>spark.jars</code> configuration) in order to link to the Datasource classes they depend on. In terms of developer experience, I don't think this pattern is foreign to Spark users today.</p> <p>Notably, nothing prohibits users from bundling their own superjars that contain all of their dependencies and deploying them to their Spark clusters. Similarly, nothing prevents integration authors from using reflection in their code. Users are given the freedom to extend and package their integrations in a way that suits them without enforcing an opaque, black-box model.</p> <p>As a separate issue, we can consider changing the Marquez agent to be loaded by the <code>spark.extraListeners</code> configuration. This would allow users to reference all of the Marquez integration dependencies by specifying the listener and the node visitors in <code>spark.jars.packages</code> so that all of the classes are loaded by the Spark <code>ClassLoader</code>. That eliminates any confusion about which components need to be loaded by which <code>ClassLoader</code>. It also simplifies testing and could enable integration in serverless environments, such as AWS Glue, where users don't have access to modify the JVM arguments.</p> <p><strong>Packaging Spark Integrations</strong></p> <p>Spark integration packages need to create a file in <code>META-INF/services/marquez.spark.agent.lifecycle.plan.DatasetSource</code> which declares a list of classes that implement the <code>marquez.spark.agent.lifecycle.plan.DatasetSource</code> interface. During startup, the main Marquez agent uses the JVM <code>ServiceLoader</code> to find all service implementations on the classpath (we need to specifically check the Spark <code>URLClassloader</code> to find implementations loaded by Spark at runtime). Combining jars requires concatenating the contents of the <code>META-INF/services/marquez.spark.agent.lifecycle.plan.DatasetSource</code> files so that all implementations are listed.</p> <p><strong>Deploying Dependencies</strong></p> <p>Currently, users deploy the Marquez integration by adding the <code>javaagent:&amp;lt;jar&amp;gt;=&lt;http://marquez_url/path/to/job&gt;</code> argument to their spark-submit args. That doesn't change with this proposal.</p> <p>What does change is that users would be required to specify the integrations they require in their <code>spark.jars</code> or <code>spark.jars.packages</code> configuration. As an example, the airflow example in the README would look like this:</p> <pre><code>from uuid import uuid4 import os ... job_name = 'job_name' jar = 'marquez-spark-0.13.1.jar' files = [f"&lt;https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/io/github/marquezproject/marquez-spark/0.13.1/marquez-spark-0.13.1.jar&gt;"] properties = { 'spark.driver.extraJavaOptions': f"-javaagent:{jar}={os.environ.get('MARQUEZ_URL')}/api/v1/namespaces/{os.getenv('MARQUEZ_NAMESPACE', 'default')}/jobs/{job_name}/runs/{uuid4()}?api_key={os.environ.get('MARQUEZ_API_KEY')}" } t1 = DataProcPySparkOperator( task_id=job_name, gcp_conn_id='google_cloud_default', project_id='project_id', cluster_name='cluster-name', region='us-west1', main='&lt;gs://bucket/your-prog.py&gt;', job_name=job_name, dataproc_pyspark_properties=properties, files=files, &lt;b&gt;#Both&lt;/b&gt; bigquery relation and bigquery marquez integration declared here dataproc_pyspark_jars='&lt;gs://spark-lib/bigquery/spark-bigquery-latest_2.12.jar,gs://my_bucket/path/to/bigquery-integration.jar&gt;', dag=dag) </code></pre> <p>Alternatively, a cluster can be created by loading the correct jars into the Spark jars directory, as described in the <a href="https://github.com/GoogleCloudDataproc/initialization-actions/tree/master/connectors">BigQuery connector docs</a>. In the same way, the…</p>

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/184|#184 package level job metadata>
<p><strong>Purpose</strong></p> <p>To expose information like the version of the job and its source repository, Marquez needs a mechanism to provide metadata in the job package when deploying to a scheduler.<br /> An example of this is deploying DAGs to an Airflow instance, but this is applicable to all package deployments in general.<br /> In some instances workflows/jobs are directly pulled from a source control system from the scheduler allowing some metadata to be inferred from the environment. In other instances, the jobs are packaged and deployed to a scheduler (example: google cloud composer or astronomer). This doc concerns the later case of providing metadata related to the source code of the job at build time.</p> <p><strong>Proposal</strong></p> <p>We define a metadata file to be added at the root of the package/deployment location. This file is named <strong>.OpenLineage.job.facets.json</strong> and is a json file with the following initial properties (that can be expanded later).</p> <p><strong>Properties:</strong></p> <p>• <strong>sourceCodeLocation.type</strong>: the source control system<br /> Examples: GIT, SVN, ... • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.url</strong>: the URL to the repository<br /> Examples: • GIT: <a href="mailto:git@github.com">git@github.com</a>:{org}/{repo}.git or <a href="https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D.git|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}.git">https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D.git|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}.git</a> • SVN: svn://&lt;your<em>ip&gt;/&lt;repository</em>name&gt; • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.path</strong>: the path in the repo containing the source files<br /> Example: path/to/my/dags<br /> It is intended that we can reconstruct a URL from that path pointing to the file defining a job. <a href="https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D/tree/%7Bverion%7D/%7Bpath%7D/%7Bfile|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}/tree/{verion}/{path}/{file">https://github.com/%7Borg%7D/%7Brepo%7D/tree/%7Bverion%7D/%7Bpath%7D/%7Bfile|https://github.com/{org}/{repo}/tree/{verion}/{path}/{file</a> path in the package} • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.version</strong>: the current version deployed (not a branch name, the actual unique version)<br /> Examples: • Git: the git sha • Svn: the revision number • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.tag</strong>: optional tag name<br /> Examples: {tag name} • <strong>sourceCodeLocation.branch</strong>:optional branch name</p> <p><strong>JSON Schema</strong></p> <pre><code>{ "$schema": "&lt;https://json-schema.org/draft/2019-09/schema&gt;", "type": "object", "properties": { "sourceCodeLocation": { "type": "object", "properties": { "type": { "type": "string" }, "url": { "type": "string" }, "path": { "type": "string" }, "version": { "type": "string" }, "branch": { "type": "string" } }, "required": [ "type", "url", "path", "version", "branch" ] } }, "required": [ "sourceCodeLocation" ] } </code></pre> <p><strong>Example:</strong></p> <p>For the DAG defined at: <a href="https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart/blob/693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691/dags/dummy_example.py">https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart/blob/693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691/dags/dummy_example.py</a></p> <pre><code>{ "sourceCodeLocation": { "type": "GIT", "url: "&lt;https://github.com/MarquezProject/marquez-airflow-quickstart.git&gt;", "path": "dags", "version": "693e35482bc2e526ced2b5f9f76ef83dec6ec691", "branch": "master" } } </code></pre>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] New release Release - OpenLineage 0.1.0 published by wslulciuc

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/releases/tag/0.1.0|Release - OpenLineage 0.1.0>
<p>OpenLineage is an <em>Open Standard</em> for lineage metadata collection designed to record metadata for a job in execution. The initial public release includes:</p> <p>• <strong>An inital specification.</strong> The the inital version <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/0.1.0/spec/OpenLineage.md"><code>1-0-0</code></a> of the OpenLineage specification defines the core model and facets. • <strong>Integrations</strong> that collect lineage metadata as OpenLineage events: • <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/tree/main/integration/airflow"><code>Apache Airflow</code></a> with support for BigQuery, Great Expectations, Postgres, Redshift, Snowflake • <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/tree/main/integration/spark"><code>Apache Spark</code></a> • <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/tree/main/integration/dbt"><code>dbt</code></a> • <strong>Clients</strong> that send OpenLineage events to an HTTP backend. Both <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/tree/main/client/java"><code>java</code></a> and <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/tree/main/client/python"><code>python</code></a> are initially supported.</p>

[OpenLineage/OpenLineage] Issue opened by julienledem

<https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/issues/207|#207 [PROPOSAL] Model a BI dashboard in the OpenLineage model>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong><br /> We want to track BI dashboards (Tableau, Looker, Superset, ...) in the lineage graph.<br /> Like a <code>Job</code> a BI dashboard has a unique identifier and can change over time. It queries underlying datasets at irregular intervals given user interactions. Those are inputs to the BI dashboard.</p> <p><strong>Proposed implementation</strong><br /> There are several ways to model this. We need to pick one.<br /> A first proposal is as follows:</p> <p>• A dashboard is a <code>Job</code>, every time it issues queries, this creates a <code>Run</code> that captures the inputs (tables being queried).</p>

<p><strong>Purpose:</strong><br /> In Snowflake, on can create a STAGE table before actually<br /> <a href="https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/create-stage.html">https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/create-stage.html</a></p> <p><strong>Proposed implementation</strong><br /> We need to update the naming spec to include the stage type in the table name to avoid conflict between a stage object and the final table.<br /> <a href="https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/main/spec/Naming.md#snowflake">https://github.com/OpenLineage/OpenLineage/blob/main/spec/Naming.md#snowflake</a></p> <p>Current: <code>snowflake://{account name}/{database}.{schema}.{table}</code><br /> Proposal: <code>snowflake://{account name}/{database}.{schema}.[STAGE.]{table}</code></p>
